00:23:24.599 --> 00:23:30.000
I feel like most of you guys.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.162
Somebody, come on.

00:23:32.162 --> 00:23:34.324
What do you think?

00:23:34.324 --> 00:23:36.607
It's going to work?

00:23:36.607 --> 00:23:37.568
No idea?

00:23:37.568 --> 00:23:41.532
What has to happen for it to
work?

00:23:41.532 --> 00:23:48.740
I'll give you a vector that has
my gene corresponding to that

00:23:48.740 --> 00:23:49.581
enzyme.

00:23:49.581 --> 00:23:51.383
It's in E.
coli.

00:23:51.383 --> 00:23:54.626
I need to make the protein.

00:23:54.626 --> 00:23:55.227
Yeah?

00:23:55.227 --> 00:23:57.990
No, it's in the vector.

00:23:57.990 --> 00:24:02.194
We cloned it into an E.
coli vector.

00:24:02.194 --> 00:24:04.357
So, that's got it.

00:24:04.357 --> 00:24:07.000
Yeah?

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.917
Well it'll have a language that
will say "start transcription",

00:24:11.917 --> 00:24:14.931
but whose language is it going
to have?

00:24:14.931 --> 00:24:18.341
It's going to have my
transcriptional stuff.

00:24:18.341 --> 00:24:20.324
Will that work in E.
coli?

00:24:20.324 --> 00:24:23.655
Even though the open reading
frame is fine,

00:24:23.655 --> 00:24:24.606
that's good.

00:24:24.606 --> 00:24:26.351
How about translation?

00:24:26.351 --> 00:24:30.000
I didn't even tell you about
that.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.801
There is actually some specific
stuff needed.

00:24:32.801 --> 00:24:34.583
That's not universal,
either.

00:24:34.583 --> 00:24:38.021
So when you get the RNA you
still have to translate it.

00:24:38.021 --> 00:24:40.822
There is another thing that
might mess us up.

00:24:40.822 --> 00:24:43.433
Do you remember anything else
about, yeah?

00:24:43.433 --> 00:24:44.579
Introns and exons?

00:24:44.579 --> 00:24:48.462
What if my gene has introns in
it, which it almost surely has?

00:24:48.462 --> 00:24:50.245
We have to get rid of those.

00:24:50.245 --> 00:24:52.091
E.
coli doesn't know what they

00:24:52.091 --> 00:24:52.346
are.

00:24:52.346 --> 00:24:54.383
It's not used to taking them
out.

00:24:54.383 --> 00:24:55.593
You see the issues?

00:24:55.593 --> 00:24:59.285
Although that's a cute thing
and that helps you find a gene

00:24:59.285 --> 00:25:01.259
from E.
coli by complementing E.

00:25:01.259 --> 00:25:03.869
coli mutant,
or maybe you could do it with

00:25:03.869 --> 00:25:07.371
yeast if you had a factor that
would replicate in yeast,

00:25:07.371 --> 00:25:11.000
it wasn't a general solution.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.311
So people had to use a whole
variety of different ways.

00:25:14.311 --> 00:25:15.476
Here's another way.

00:25:15.476 --> 00:25:17.929
You know that you have that
genetic code.

00:25:17.929 --> 00:25:19.768
That was worked out years ago.

00:25:19.768 --> 00:25:22.650
So let's say I was a
biochemist, and I'd found a

00:25:22.650 --> 00:25:25.778
protein that I was interested
in, and I purified it,

00:25:25.778 --> 00:25:29.518
and they got it out to single
protein, and then I could cut it

00:25:29.518 --> 00:25:33.136
up with things that proteases
that will cut the protein into

00:25:33.136 --> 00:25:37.000
pieces, and there are ways of
sequencing protein.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:40.864
I'm not going to tell you how
it works in this course.

00:25:40.864 --> 00:25:42.614
We just don't have time.

00:25:42.614 --> 00:25:46.697
But you can get the sequence of
little pieces of protein.

00:25:46.697 --> 00:25:50.927
And let's imagine that this was
the sequence of part of the

00:25:50.927 --> 00:25:52.677
protein that I purified.

00:25:52.677 --> 00:25:55.666
It's one of my enzymes [SOUND
OFF/THEN ON]

00:25:55.666 --> 00:25:57.854
and I'd like to find the gene.

00:25:57.854 --> 00:26:02.010
Well, how could I use that
information to figure out where

00:26:02.010 --> 00:26:05.000
the gene is in this library?

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:07.401
So here's the strategy.

00:26:07.401 --> 00:26:12.831
We get out the genetic code,
which Gobind Khorana and

00:26:12.831 --> 00:26:17.947
Marshall Nirenberg helped work
out, and we say OK,

00:26:17.947 --> 00:26:24.212
alanine, and if you look it up,
what you'll find is that it's

00:26:24.212 --> 00:26:27.658
GC, and then it can be A T C or
G.

00:26:27.658 --> 00:26:31.000
It can be any of those.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:34.482
If we look up what the codon
for aspartate.

00:26:34.482 --> 00:26:38.960
We'll find that there's a G or
an A, but it could be T,

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:40.370
or it could be C.

00:26:40.370 --> 00:26:43.356
We look up lysine;
it'll mostly be A,

00:26:43.356 --> 00:26:45.263
but it could be A or G.

00:26:45.263 --> 00:26:50.156
You'll notice the variation of
those things is almost all in

00:26:50.156 --> 00:26:53.556
the third codon if that hadn't
struck you.

00:26:53.556 --> 00:26:58.200
Same thing with threonine:
A, C, and this is another one;

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:00.936
therefore codons that encode
this.

00:27:00.936 --> 00:27:05.000
And this one asparagine is
that.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:13.653
So knowing that piece of the
protein doesn't define a unique

00:27:13.653 --> 00:27:14.973
sequence.

00:27:14.973 --> 00:27:23.186
Though, what we could do it is
we could synthesize what's

00:27:23.186 --> 00:27:27.000
called a mixed probe.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:32.849
And that would mean when we are
going to synthesize this DNA and

00:27:32.849 --> 00:27:36.007
we'd start with a G building
block.

00:27:36.007 --> 00:27:39.349
And then we'd add a C building
block.

00:27:39.349 --> 00:27:41.578
So, now we made G and C.

00:27:41.578 --> 00:27:46.407
And at the next step,
we'd add an equal mixture of A,

00:27:46.407 --> 00:27:47.521
T, G, and C.

00:27:47.521 --> 00:27:53.092
So, what we would get out of
that would be we'd be getting G,

00:27:53.092 --> 00:27:57.828
and then the next biosynthetic
step would give us G,

00:27:57.828 --> 00:27:58.014
C.

00:27:58.014 --> 00:28:02.842
And then the next biochemical
step would give us GCA,

00:28:02.842 --> 00:28:06.000
GCT, GCC, or GCG.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.553
At the next step,
we'd add a G.

00:28:08.553 --> 00:28:11.446
So everyone of these would get
a G.

00:28:11.446 --> 00:28:15.446
Everyone would get an A,
and then the next step,

00:28:15.446 --> 00:28:16.978
they would branch.

00:28:16.978 --> 00:28:21.829
And if you follow that out,
you'll see by the end you have

00:28:21.829 --> 00:28:23.531
a mixture of probes.

00:28:23.531 --> 00:28:28.638
One of them is going to be the
right one that you find in the

00:28:28.638 --> 00:28:30.000
DNA.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.364
Now if you work out the number
of possibilities,

00:28:33.364 --> 00:28:37.587
you'll discover that most of
the time there is only going to

00:28:37.587 --> 00:28:39.520
be one probe that's unique.

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:43.099
Once you get to about 20
nucleotides, any sequence,

00:28:43.099 --> 00:28:46.750
on average, is represented once
in the human genome.

00:28:46.750 --> 00:28:49.900
So as long as you make the
probe long enough,

00:28:49.900 --> 00:28:53.980
one of the things in your
mixture will be a defined probe.

00:28:53.980 --> 00:28:58.275
So, what we can take is we have
all these different pieces of

00:28:58.275 --> 00:29:03.000
DNA that are the logical
variants you can see here.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:06.805
And then we would label the
probe with P32.

00:29:06.805 --> 00:29:10.974
It's a radioactive isotope,
and it's very easy.

00:29:10.974 --> 00:29:14.598
You can add it to a five-prime
phosphate.

00:29:14.598 --> 00:29:19.491
There's a special enzyme that
will very easily take the

00:29:19.491 --> 00:29:23.388
terminal phosphate from ATP and
put it over.

00:29:23.388 --> 00:29:26.650
It doesn't really [SOUND
OFF/THEN ON]

00:29:26.650 --> 00:29:31.000
for this course how we get it
there.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:35.011
But we can do is radioactively
label the probe.

00:29:35.011 --> 00:29:37.627
So now we've got this mixture.

00:29:37.627 --> 00:29:42.860
And, somewhere in this library
is a piece of DNA that's going

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:47.569
to have the gene that's encoding
the protein that we're

00:29:47.569 --> 00:29:48.790
interested in.

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:52.976
So, how do you go about trying
to deal with that?

00:29:52.976 --> 00:29:56.290
So, what we'll do is we'll
plate our E.

00:29:56.290 --> 00:30:01.000
coli library onto a bunch of
Petri plates.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:05.218
So, I won't put too many
colonies on here,

00:30:05.218 --> 00:30:08.408
so we can sort of see a
pattern.

00:30:08.408 --> 00:30:14.479
But, we'd have probably a lot
of them, and we'd have a bunch

00:30:14.479 --> 00:30:15.508
of plates.

00:30:15.508 --> 00:30:21.887
You can work out statistically
how many plates you have to have

00:30:21.887 --> 00:30:26.929
to have a chance of finding your
gene of interest.

00:30:26.929 --> 00:30:33.000
Then what we do,
is lay a membrane on the plate.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:39.857
It's a particular type of
membrane, and what that will do

00:30:39.857 --> 00:30:45.857
is it will make a copy of
everything that's there,

00:30:45.857 --> 00:30:49.897
and we're going to save the
plate.

00:30:49.897 --> 00:30:55.040
And then we're going to treat
the membrane,

00:30:55.040 --> 00:30:55.408
OK?

00:30:55.408 --> 00:31:03.000
We've got a membrane that's got
an identical pattern.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:08.605
They've got some of the
bacteria from the colonies stuck

00:31:08.605 --> 00:31:12.885
at the corresponding parts on
the membrane.

00:31:12.885 --> 00:31:18.286
We're going to lyse the E.
coli; that means break them

00:31:18.286 --> 00:31:21.853
open so all their insides spill
out.

00:31:21.853 --> 00:31:27.254
We will denature the DNA by
treating with a condition.

00:31:27.254 --> 00:31:31.840
You can, for example,
vary the pH and make the

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:35.000
strands come apart.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:39.980
That gives single stranded DNA,
"ss" I'm using as an

00:31:39.980 --> 00:31:46.035
abbreviation for single strand
of the strands you pulled apart.

00:31:46.035 --> 00:31:49.160
And, this sticks to the
membrane.

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:53.652
So, now we've got,
at every one of these little

00:31:53.652 --> 00:32:00.000
positions on the membrane
something that looks like this.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:05.557
Here's the membrane,
and there's some sort of single

00:32:05.557 --> 00:32:11.769
stranded DNA that's stuck to the
membrane in that fashion.

00:32:11.769 --> 00:32:18.525
The DNA that's stuck here came
from the bacterium here that had

00:32:18.525 --> 00:32:20.705
a particular insert.

00:32:20.705 --> 00:32:26.916
Over here, we have all the E.
coli DNA and the vector DNA,

00:32:26.916 --> 00:32:34.000
but we will have a different
piece of DNA in the vector.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:35.279
Everybody with me?

00:32:35.279 --> 00:32:39.404
OK, so if we were now to take
our radioactive probe that we

00:32:39.404 --> 00:32:42.746
made up there and get the
conditions just right,

00:32:42.746 --> 00:32:46.942
that single stranded probe will
come in, and it will try and

00:32:46.942 --> 00:32:48.364
find its complement.

00:32:48.364 --> 00:32:52.417
It'll form hydrogen bonds
because that's the lowest energy

00:32:52.417 --> 00:32:52.773
well.

00:32:52.773 --> 00:32:55.617
And, we think about it
thermodynamically.

00:32:55.617 --> 00:32:59.244
And, if we can get it right,
the temperature and the

00:32:59.244 --> 00:33:02.586
conditions right,
nothing will stick unless it's

00:33:02.586 --> 00:33:06.000
an exact match to the sequence.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:13.190
And, if we get the right probe
that can form hydrogen bonds

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:20.008
with everything on here,
and it's got P32 at this point,

00:33:20.008 --> 00:33:26.950
what will happen is we'll have
now, the probe will stick,

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:34.264
say, to this particular colony,
now with radioactivity right

00:33:34.264 --> 00:33:36.000
there.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:42.792
So, put some photographic film
over the membrane,

00:33:42.792 --> 00:33:51.000
and right here there's P32,
and that'll expose the film and

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.839
nowhere else.

00:33:52.839 --> 00:33:59.773
And then, when we develop,
what we'll find is one,

00:33:59.773 --> 00:34:06.000
if this works well,
anyway, one spot.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.713
So, now we know that that
piece, that colony had a piece

00:34:09.713 --> 00:34:13.697
of human DNA in it that was
related to the sequence from the

00:34:13.697 --> 00:34:15.588
protein that I had purified.

00:34:15.588 --> 00:34:19.099
So we go back to this colony,
I think our things have

00:34:19.099 --> 00:34:21.935
probably migrated around a
little bit here.

00:34:21.935 --> 00:34:25.784
Let's move this up just a
little bit, and make it a little

00:34:25.784 --> 00:34:27.000
better.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.166
So this one is this one.

00:34:29.166 --> 00:34:33.859
So, now I can go back to this
colony and pick it out.

00:34:33.859 --> 00:34:36.657
And, let's say it's this
insert.

00:34:36.657 --> 00:34:41.622
So, now I've found I can
sequence the rest of that piece

00:34:41.622 --> 00:34:42.254
of DNA.

00:34:42.254 --> 00:34:46.496
We'll talk about how we
sequence DNA in the next

00:34:46.496 --> 00:34:47.218
lecture.

00:34:47.218 --> 00:34:52.904
So that's an alternative way of
identifying a clone of interest.

00:34:52.904 --> 00:34:57.959
There was a particularly
painful way of finding a gene in

00:34:57.959 --> 00:35:05.000
a library that we for the most
part do not have to do any more.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:11.400
It was called positional
cloning.

00:35:11.400 --> 00:35:23.199
And for example the gene that
when it's broken causes cystic

00:35:23.199 --> 00:35:32.000
fibrosis, it's a very difficult
disease.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:36.909
Humans who have cystic
fibrosis have a very tough time.

00:35:36.909 --> 00:35:41.818
So there's a great deal of
interest in finding the gene

00:35:41.818 --> 00:35:44.818
that was broken in these
patients.

00:35:44.818 --> 00:35:49.000
Human geneticists,
I showed you something about

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:52.545
pedigrees, they would have a
chromosome.

00:35:52.545 --> 00:35:57.272
They might have banding
patterns, and they would have

00:35:57.272 --> 00:36:03.090
figured out that somewhere along
the chromosome that the gene for

00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:08.636
cystic fibrosis lay somewhere
between two genetic markers that

00:36:08.636 --> 00:36:12.000
they had identified.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.792
Now, the amount of DNA between
something that you knew that the

00:36:15.792 --> 00:36:18.300
gene was here,
and something knew that the

00:36:18.300 --> 00:36:20.074
gene was there,
could be huge.

00:36:20.074 --> 00:36:22.827
It could be many,
many, many times the size of

00:36:22.827 --> 00:36:24.172
the E.
coli chromosome.

00:36:24.172 --> 00:36:27.476
So, what people would do is
they'd clone something from

00:36:27.476 --> 00:36:31.329
here, a little piece of DNA from
there, and also clone something

00:36:31.329 --> 00:36:35.000
and they get a little piece of
DNA from there.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:38.907
And then they go into the
library, and they try and find

00:36:38.907 --> 00:36:43.311
something that had this DNA and
something that extended in this

00:36:43.311 --> 00:36:45.087
direction the little bit.

00:36:45.087 --> 00:36:49.562
By the sort of thing you'd have
marker A somewhere in the middle

00:36:49.562 --> 00:36:53.896
of the cystic fibrosis gene but
you didn't know exactly where.

00:36:53.896 --> 00:36:58.229
You'd clone a little piece of
DNA and use that to find another

00:36:58.229 --> 00:37:01.000
one that overlapped with it.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.516
And that you'd find,
use that to find another piece

00:37:04.516 --> 00:37:05.008
of DNA.

00:37:05.008 --> 00:37:09.087
You'd walk your way over this
way, and you'd start the same

00:37:09.087 --> 00:37:10.846
process at the other end.

00:37:10.846 --> 00:37:15.206
And, every one of these things,
the same kind of operation that

00:37:15.206 --> 00:37:17.808
we've got here,
so cycles, and cycles,

00:37:17.808 --> 00:37:21.606
and cycles of acquiring the
next adjacent piece of DNA,

00:37:21.606 --> 00:37:23.786
and working your way along
here.

00:37:23.786 --> 00:37:27.514
And you had to use more than
one different restriction

00:37:27.514 --> 00:37:33.000
enzymes, otherwise you wouldn't
be able to get these overlaps.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.237
And by doing that,
eventually they were able to

00:37:36.237 --> 00:37:39.475
get all the DNA that was between
these markers.

00:37:39.475 --> 00:37:43.487
They knew the cystic fibrosis
gene was there from the maps

00:37:43.487 --> 00:37:46.373
they had made by studying human
pedigrees.

00:37:46.373 --> 00:37:50.033
And then, once you knew the
sequence, then you'd take

00:37:50.033 --> 00:37:52.919
candidate genes,
and you'd take a bunch of

00:37:52.919 --> 00:37:56.861
cystic fibrosis patients,
and you'd start to see if every

00:37:56.861 --> 00:38:02.000
person who had cystic fibrosis
had a mutation in that gene.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.442
And, eventually they got it.

00:38:04.442 --> 00:38:09.501
That process in the case of
cystic fibrosis took five years

00:38:09.501 --> 00:38:12.728
to do that with a huge team of
people.

00:38:12.728 --> 00:38:15.694
And, I guess it was from
1985-1990.

00:38:15.694 --> 00:38:19.271
If you wanted to do that
experiment today.

00:38:19.271 --> 00:38:24.417
We come now to one of the most
widely used ways to finding a

00:38:24.417 --> 00:38:28.080
gene of interest,
and that is you go to the

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:30.000
computer.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:32.751
The whole human genome sequence
is in there.

00:38:32.751 --> 00:38:35.184
If we were to do that
experiment today,

00:38:35.184 --> 00:38:37.744
we'd say, well,
I know what this gene is,

00:38:37.744 --> 00:38:40.304
so you look that gene up in the
database.

00:38:40.304 --> 00:38:44.143
And you knew what this gene was
and you look up the database.

00:38:44.143 --> 00:38:47.599
Then you just look at all the
DNA that's in the middle.

00:38:47.599 --> 00:38:50.864
And you'd see a whole series of
open reading frames.

00:38:50.864 --> 00:38:54.255
And you'd probably say,
well, what do I know about the

00:38:54.255 --> 00:38:55.983
biology of cystic fibrosis?

00:38:55.983 --> 00:38:57.327
Could I make a guess?

00:38:57.327 --> 00:38:58.927
Is it a membrane protein?

00:38:58.927 --> 00:39:02.000
Is it not a membrane protein?

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:05.009
And, there are certain
characteristics that would

00:39:05.009 --> 00:39:07.141
probably allow you to make a
guess.

00:39:07.141 --> 00:39:10.778
And then, you could jump right
in and start sequencing DNA.

00:39:10.778 --> 00:39:14.289
You could start the experiment
practically that afternoon

00:39:14.289 --> 00:39:16.045
instead of five years later.

00:39:16.045 --> 00:39:19.807
So, if you look back from the
literature, you'll find some of

00:39:19.807 --> 00:39:22.315
the key genes;
in fact, in human biology,

00:39:22.315 --> 00:39:25.826
we're isolated by this very
painful process of positional

00:39:25.826 --> 00:39:28.836
cloning, and you hardly ever
have to do that now.

00:39:28.836 --> 00:39:31.782
It may be the odd case where
something's needed,

00:39:31.782 --> 00:39:34.855
but most of the stuff now,
there are these amazing

00:39:34.855 --> 00:39:38.742
databases, and I'll give you the
URL for it at the beginning of

00:39:38.742 --> 00:39:41.000
next lecture.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:45.281
And I'll show you when,
this is an experiment in which

00:39:45.281 --> 00:39:48.674
someone took this gene for
cystic fibrosis.

00:39:48.674 --> 00:39:53.116
It is a membrane protein,
and it's one of those proteins

00:39:53.116 --> 00:39:57.317
that mediates the passage of
chloride ions across the

00:39:57.317 --> 00:39:58.044
membrane.

00:39:58.044 --> 00:40:01.841
And, if that gets broken,
you end up with cystic

00:40:01.841 --> 00:40:02.568
fibrosis.

00:40:02.568 --> 00:40:06.849
What someone has done here is
they've taken that green

00:40:06.849 --> 00:40:10.000
fluorescent protein gene.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.809
And, they've fused it to the
end of the cystic fibrosis gene.

00:40:14.809 --> 00:40:18.736
So, you can tell where the
cystic fibrosis gene is

00:40:18.736 --> 00:40:22.824
localized in a lung cell by
looking to see where the

00:40:22.824 --> 00:40:24.106
fluorescence is.

00:40:24.106 --> 00:40:28.755
And, I think you can see that
the fluorescence is out there

00:40:28.755 --> 00:40:31.000
along the membrane.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:35.860
OK, so at the beginning of next
lecture, I'll introduce you to

00:40:35.860 --> 00:40:39.445
how we take one of these
recombinant plasmids,

00:40:39.445 --> 00:40:42.632
and make what's called a
restriction map.

00:40:42.632 --> 00:40:47.014
It's using a very simple,
little piece of apparatus like

00:40:47.014 --> 00:40:51.396
that, and we'll go in and tell
you about DNA sequencing,

00:40:51.396 --> 00:40:55.619
and this PCR technique you've
heard, preliminary chain

00:40:55.619 --> 00:40:58.552
reaction that you've heard so
much about, OK?

